<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1548,2005]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[151,361,1548,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[151,361,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ornithia mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sturm, J." box="[683,832,1548,1572]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref16399" refString="Sturm, J. (1843) Catalog der Kafer-Sammlung von Jacob Sturm. Gedruckt auf Kosten des Verfassers, Nurnberg, 386 pp., 6 pls." type="book" year="1843">Sturm (1843)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName box="[869,1077,1548,1573]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ozodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[869,1077,1548,1573]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ozodes mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. A year later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Guerin-Meneville, F. E." pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref15316" refString="Guerin-Meneville, F. E. (1844) Iconographie du regne animal de G. Cuvier, ou representation d'apres nature de l'une des especes les plus remarquables et souvent non figurees de chaque genre d'animaux. Avec un texte descriptif mis au courant de la science. Ouvrage pouvant servir d'atlas a tous les traites de zoologie. Insectes. Fol. 7. Bailliere, Paris, 576 pp." type="book" year="1844">Guérin-Méneville (1844)</bibRefCitation>
described the same species as 
<taxonomicName box="[592,873,1583,1608]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[592,873,1583,1608]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Trichophorus chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, also from 
<collectingCountry box="[1011,1100,1583,1608]" name="Mexico" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. In the same year, 
<bibRefCitation author="Chevrolat, L. A. A." pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="197 - 199" refId="ref14981" refString="Chevrolat, L. A. A. (1844) Catalolg der Kaefer-Sammlung von Jacob Sturm. Nuremberg, 1843. Revue Zoologique, 7, 197 - 199." type="journal article" year="1844">Chevrolat (1844)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized these species: “28. 
<taxonomicName authority="Mexicanus, St." authorityName="Mexicanus, St." box="[603,857,1620,1645]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ozodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[603,813,1620,1645]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ozodes Mexicanus</emphasis>
, St.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority=", Chev. Cat. Dej. Trich. Chevrolatii, Guerin" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentipictus">
<emphasis box="[873,1178,1620,1645]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Trichophorus argentipictus</emphasis>
, Chev. Cat. Dej. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Trich. Chevrolatii</emphasis>
, Guérin
</taxonomicName>
texte de l’Icon. du rég. animal Ins. p. 228).” 
<bibRefCitation author="White, A." box="[875,1027,1655,1680]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref16638" refString="White, A. (1853) Catalogue of the coleopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Fol. 7. Longicornia 1. British Museum, London, 174 pp." type="book" year="1853">White (1853)</bibRefCitation>
, apparently, observed the synonymy proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chevrolat, L. A. A." box="[297,492,1692,1717]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="197 - 199" refId="ref14981" refString="Chevrolat, L. A. A. (1844) Catalolg der Kaefer-Sammlung von Jacob Sturm. Nuremberg, 1843. Revue Zoologique, 7, 197 - 199." type="journal article" year="1844">Chevrolat (1844)</bibRefCitation>
, and listed the following species as synonyms of 
<taxonomicName box="[1052,1331,1692,1717]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[1052,1331,1692,1717]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Trichophorus chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(the first three, based on Dejean’s 1836 catalogue): 
<taxonomicName authority="Dupont" authorityName="Dupont" box="[641,971,1727,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulphureosignatus">
<emphasis box="[641,875,1727,1752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">T. sulphureosignatus</emphasis>
Dupont
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName authority=", Chevrolat" authorityName="Chevrolat" box="[986,1293,1727,1752]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="croceinotatus">
<emphasis box="[986,1167,1729,1752]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">T. croceinotatus</emphasis>
, Chevrolat
</taxonomicName>
(female); 
<taxonomicName authority="Chevrolat" authorityName="Chevrolat" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argenteipictus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">T. argenteipictus</emphasis>
Chevrolat
</taxonomicName>
(male); and 
<taxonomicName authority="Sturm. Nevertheless" authorityName="Sturm. Nevertheless" box="[593,1055,1764,1789]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ozodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis box="[593,806,1764,1789]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ozodes mexicanus</emphasis>
Sturm. Nevertheless
</taxonomicName>
, considering the dates of 
<bibRefCitation author="Sturm, J." pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref16399" refString="Sturm, J. (1843) Catalog der Kafer-Sammlung von Jacob Sturm. Gedruckt auf Kosten des Verfassers, Nurnberg, 386 pp., 6 pls." type="book" year="1843">Sturm (1843)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Guerin-Meneville, F. E." box="[280,563,1799,1824]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref15316" refString="Guerin-Meneville, F. E. (1844) Iconographie du regne animal de G. Cuvier, ou representation d'apres nature de l'une des especes les plus remarquables et souvent non figurees de chaque genre d'animaux. Avec un texte descriptif mis au courant de la science. Ouvrage pouvant servir d'atlas a tous les traites de zoologie. Insectes. Fol. 7. Bailliere, Paris, 576 pp." type="book" year="1844">Guérin-Méneville (1844)</bibRefCitation>
as correct, evidently, 
<taxonomicName box="[808,1086,1799,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[808,1086,1799,1824]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Trichophorus chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ozodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ozodes mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and not the opposite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1548,2005]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1437,151,752]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, J." box="[199,394,1871,1896]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="1 - 352" refId="ref16483" refString="Thomson, J. (1864) Systema cerambycidarum ou expose de tous les genres compris dans la famille des cerambycides et familles limitrophes. H. Dessain, Liege, pp. 1 - 352." type="book chapter" year="1864">Thomson (1864)</bibRefCitation>
erected the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[633,730,1871,1896]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[633,730,1871,1896]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ornithia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and followed the synonymies proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="White, A." box="[1271,1431,1871,1896]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref16638" refString="White, A. (1853) Catalogue of the coleopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Fol. 7. Longicornia 1. British Museum, London, 174 pp." type="book" year="1853">White (1853)</bibRefCitation>
, considering the name 
<taxonomicName box="[399,547,1908,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[399,547,1908,1933]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">T. chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as being the valid name of the species. During the time between 
<bibRefCitation author="White, A." box="[1285,1436,1908,1933]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref16638" refString="White, A. (1853) Catalogue of the coleopterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Fol. 7. Longicornia 1. British Museum, London, 174 pp." type="book" year="1853">White (1853)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Mason, F. R." box="[198,358,1944,1968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="22 - 24" refId="ref15831" refString="Mason, F. R. (1910) Collecting beetles in Mexico. The Canadian Entomologist, 42 (1), 22 - 24. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 4222 - 1" type="journal article" year="1910">Mason (1910)</bibRefCitation>
, only 
<bibRefCitation author="Gemminger, M." box="[427,642,1943,1968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" pagination="2989 - 3232" refId="ref15245" refString="Gemminger, M. (1873) Catalogus Coleopterorum hucusque descriptorum synonymicus et systematicus. Fol. 10. Gummi, Monachii, 244 pp. [pp. 2989 - 3232]" type="book chapter" year="1873">Gemminger (1873)</bibRefCitation>
correctly reported 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[856,1068,1943,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[856,1068,1943,1968]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ornithia mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the valid name of the species. It was only after 
<bibRefCitation author="Aurivillius, C." box="[346,550,1980,2005]" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" refId="ref14506" refString="Aurivillius, C. (1912) Coleopterorum Catalogus. Pars 39. Cerambycidae: Cerambycinae. W. Junk, Berlin, 574 pp." type="book" year="1912">Aurivillius (1912)</bibRefCitation>
that 
<taxonomicName box="[609,757,1980,2005]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Trichophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[609,757,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">T. chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was finally considered as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1224,1436,1980,2005]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[1224,1436,1980,2005]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="72">Ornithia mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by all authors, except 
<bibRefCitation author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[407,607,151,176]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref16520" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 (3), 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann (1960)</bibRefCitation>
, who described 
<taxonomicName box="[795,1146,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="chevrolatii" subSpecies="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[795,1146,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Ornithia chevrolatii zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Tippmann, F. F." pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref16520" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 (3), 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann (1960)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName box="[232,386,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chevrolatii">
<emphasis box="[232,386,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">O. chevrolatii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[440,581,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[440,581,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were described in the same year, and it was difficult to decide which had the priority.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1437,151,752]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
Recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez-Flores, O. &amp; Toledo-Hernandez, V. H. &amp; Zaldivar-Riveron, A." box="[311,599,260,285]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="71 - 79" refId="ref16260" refString="Perez-Flores, O., Toledo-Hernandez, V. H. &amp; Zaldivar-Riveron, A. (2017) Uso del codigo de barras de la vida para detectar problemas taxonomicos en Cerambycidae (Coleoptera: Chrysomeloidea) de un bosque tropical caducifolio. Revista Mexicana de Biodiversidad, 88, 71 - 79. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. rmb. 2017.01.014" type="journal article" year="2017">
Pérez-Flores 
<emphasis box="[460,517,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">et al.</emphasis>
(2017)
</bibRefCitation>
reported (translated): “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[863,960,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[863,960,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Ornithia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—This monotypic genus is represented by 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[151,293,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[151,293,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[306,403,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4, Estoloides jaliscana, holotype female: 1, Dorsal habitus, 2, Ventral habitus; 3, Lateral habitus; 4, Head, frontal view. 5–8, Allotigrinestola nuevoleonis, holotype female: 5, Dorsal habitus, 6, Ventral habitus; 7, Lateral habitus; 8, Head, frontal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614380/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Figure 5</figureCitation>
), which has 2 recognized subspecies, 
<emphasis box="[827,1071,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[827,923,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ornithia</taxonomicName>
m. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[964,1071,297,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1125,1378,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[1125,1221,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ornithia</taxonomicName>
m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1262,1378,297,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">zapotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. The feature proposed to distinguish these subspecies is the coloration of the bands on the pronotum (
<bibRefCitation author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[1233,1424,332,357]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref16520" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 (3), 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann, 1960</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<emphasis box="[181,356,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[249,356,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, these bands vary from white to yellowish, while in 
<emphasis box="[940,1125,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1008,1125,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">zapotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
they are lemon yellow. The molecular results delimited 2 molecular taxonomic units, one for specimens with clearly clavate and white bands on the pronotum and elytra (
<figureCitation box="[477,685,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4, Estoloides jaliscana, holotype female: 1, Dorsal habitus, 2, Ventral habitus; 3, Lateral habitus; 4, Head, frontal view. 5–8, Allotigrinestola nuevoleonis, holotype female: 5, Dorsal habitus, 6, Ventral habitus; 7, Lateral habitus; 8, Head, frontal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614380/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Figures 5C and D</figureCitation>
); and another represented by specimens with yellow bands on the pronotum and elytra (
<figureCitation box="[396,603,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[189,1401,195,1921]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. 1–4, Estoloides jaliscana, holotype female: 1, Dorsal habitus, 2, Ventral habitus; 3, Lateral habitus; 4, Head, frontal view. 5–8, Allotigrinestola nuevoleonis, holotype female: 5, Dorsal habitus, 6, Ventral habitus; 7, Lateral habitus; 8, Head, frontal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614380/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Figures 5A and B</figureCitation>
). These results support the assignment of species for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1864" box="[1213,1310,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1213,1310,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Ornithia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
previously proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sturm, J." box="[295,444,512,536]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" refId="ref16399" refString="Sturm, J. (1843) Catalog der Kafer-Sammlung von Jacob Sturm. Gedruckt auf Kosten des Verfassers, Nurnberg, 386 pp., 6 pls." type="book" year="1843">Sturm (1843)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[498,698,511,536]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref16520" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 (3), 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann (1960)</bibRefCitation>
.” However, these statements encompassed serious mistakes. First, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tippmann, F. F." box="[151,350,548,573]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" pagination="82 - 217" refId="ref16520" refString="Tippmann, F. F. (1960) Studien uber neotropische Longicornier III (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Koleopterologische Rundschau, 37 (3), 82 - 217." type="journal article" year="1960">Tippmann (1960)</bibRefCitation>
did not establish the subspecies based only on pronotal pubescence; second, the color of the pronotal and elytral pubescence is notably variable, from distinctly white to distinctly yellow, with several degrees between these two extremes; third, all specimens of their figure 5 belong to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1038,1378,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="mexicana" subSpecies="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[1038,1378,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Ornithia mexicana zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and finally, and most important, the conclusions based on molecular analysis only separate males and females of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[151,268,693,716]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">zapotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
(males with femora distinctly clavate—their figures 5C and D—from females with femora less distinctly clavate—their figures 5A and B), and not the two subspecies.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1107,1998,2020]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614388/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" startId="14.[151,250,1998,2020]" targetBox="[151,1436,855,1925]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1107,1998,2020]" box="[151,1107,1998,2020]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,281,1998,2020]" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">FIGURE 40</emphasis>
. Map of distribution of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[524,715,1998,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[524,715,1998,2020]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">Ornithia mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(circles) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[853,989,1999,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[853,989,1999,2020]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="73">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(triangles).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614390/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" startId="15.[151,264,1407,1430]" targetBox="[151,1436,193,1387]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1407,1461]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,334,1407,1430]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">FIGURES 41–44</emphasis>
. Mating pairs. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[495,557,1408,1429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">41–42</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[572,765,1408,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[572,765,1408,1430]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Ornithia 
<taxonomicName box="[668,765,1409,1430]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from Calakmul, Campeche, Mexico. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1157,1220,1408,1429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">43–44</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1235,1436,1408,1430]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[1235,1436,1408,1430]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Ornithia zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from San Blas, Nayarit, Mexico.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1505,2034]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
As it is possible to see in the map (
<figureCitation box="[592,676,1505,1530]" captionStart="FIGURE 40" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1998,2020]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,855,1925]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,855,1925]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 40. Map of distribution of Ornithia mexicana (circles) and O. zapotensis (triangles)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614388/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
), in western 
<collectingCountry box="[819,907,1505,1530]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, nearly all specimens examined by us, or those which we received data from other collections, belong to 
<emphasis box="[809,997,1542,1566]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[880,997,1543,1566]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">zapotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
, while in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1202,1288,1541,1566]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
100% of the specimens belong to 
<emphasis box="[389,566,1578,1602]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[459,566,1579,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. However, there are some specimens of 
<emphasis box="[1025,1202,1578,1602]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1095,1202,1579,1602]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
collected in western 
<collectingCountry box="[151,239,1613,1638]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and a good amount in central 
<collectingCountry box="[591,680,1613,1638]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. It is important to note that there are specimens of both subspecies collected in the same place in 
<collectingCountry box="[511,596,1649,1674]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and Central America. The most southern specimen of 
<emphasis box="[1243,1435,1650,1674]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1319,1435,1651,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">zapotensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
collected is from northern 
<collectingCountry box="[448,566,1685,1710]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, while the most southern 
<emphasis box="[852,1028,1686,1710]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
O. m. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[921,1028,1687,1710]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">mexicana</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
occurs near southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1274,1366,1687,1710]" name="Panama" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Panama</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,1505,2034]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1437,151,608]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Following the most common definition of subspecies, proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, E. &amp; Ashlock, P. D." box="[961,1239,1721,1746]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" refId="ref15871" refString="Mayr, E. &amp; Ashlock, P. D. (1991) Principles of Systematic Zoology. 2 nd edn. McGraw-Hill, New York, 475 pp." type="book" year="1991">Mayr &amp; Ashlock (1991)</bibRefCitation>
: &quot;an aggregate of phenotypically similar populations of a species inhabiting a geographic subdivision of the range of that species and differing taxonomically from other populations of that species,&quot; and considering that these populations are not reproductively isolated from each other (
<bibRefCitation author="Mayr, E." box="[617,754,1830,1854]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" refId="ref15902" refString="Mayr, E. (1942) Systematics and the Origin of Species. Columbia University Press, New York, 334 pp." type="book" year="1942">Mayr, 1942</bibRefCitation>
), we would expect to see some hybridization in the contact zone (when it exists). However, we did not examine any specimen showing a hybrid form. Accordingly, it is not possible to consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[382,534,1902,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[382,534,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[550,685,1901,1926]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–39" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1884,1907]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,518,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,517,1863]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 25–39. Dorsal habitus. 25–37, Ornithia mexicana: 25, male from Mexico; 26, male from Mexico (Chiapas); 27, male from Mexico (Puebla); 28, male from Costa Rica; 29, male from Mexico (Puebla); 30, male from Nicaragua; 31, male from Mexico (Veracruz); 32, male from Mexico (Veracruz); 33, female from Mexico (Puebla); 34, female from Mexico; 35, female from Costa Rica; 36, female from Mexico (Puebla); 37, female from Mexico. 38–39, Ornithia zapotensis, males: 38, from Nicaragua; 39, from Mexico (Nayarit)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614386/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Figs. 38–39</figureCitation>
) as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[911,1053,1902,1926]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[911,1053,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1069,1207,1901,1926]" captionStart="FIGURES 25–39" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1884,1907]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,518,1862]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,517,1863]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 25–39. Dorsal habitus. 25–37, Ornithia mexicana: 25, male from Mexico; 26, male from Mexico (Chiapas); 27, male from Mexico (Puebla); 28, male from Costa Rica; 29, male from Mexico (Puebla); 30, male from Nicaragua; 31, male from Mexico (Veracruz); 32, male from Mexico (Veracruz); 33, female from Mexico (Puebla); 34, female from Mexico; 35, female from Costa Rica; 36, female from Mexico (Puebla); 37, female from Mexico. 38–39, Ornithia zapotensis, males: 38, from Nicaragua; 39, from Mexico (Nayarit)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614386/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Figs. 25–37</figureCitation>
), especially because the subspecies would tend to disappear, especially in Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[880,966,1937,1962]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and Central America, due to the lack of isolated areas of each subspecies. We also considered the possibility of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[963,1115,1974,1998]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[963,1115,1974,1998]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
being just a variation of the typical form of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[327,470,2010,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[327,470,2010,2034]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, if 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[624,776,2010,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[624,776,2010,2034]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a variation of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[992,1134,2010,2034]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[992,1134,2010,2034]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we would find specimens showing other elytral patterns, intermediate between the two “subspecies,, independently of the geographic area. Based on these considerations, we propose that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[686,836,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[686,836,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a distinct species morphologically very close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. To reinforce this decision, although it is not conclusive evidence, we are providing photographs of two couples in copula (
<figureCitation box="[368,507,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1407,1430]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1387]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1387]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Mating pairs. 41–42, Ornithia mexicana from Calakmul, Campeche, Mexico. 43–44, Ornithia zapotensis from San Blas, Nayarit, Mexico." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614390/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">Figs. 41–44</figureCitation>
), showing that each partner belongs to the same “subspecies.” The couples of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[285,416,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–44" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1407,1430]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1387]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1387]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 41–44. Mating pairs. 41–42, Ornithia mexicana from Calakmul, Campeche, Mexico. 43–44, Ornithia zapotensis from San Blas, Nayarit, Mexico." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2614390/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">Figs. 43-44</figureCitation>
) were photographed in 
<collectingRegion box="[690,777,295,320]" country="Mexico" name="Nayarit" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">Nayarit</collectingRegion>
, a Mexican state neighboring 
<collectingRegion box="[1123,1202,295,320]" country="Mexico" name="Jalisco" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">Jalisco</collectingRegion>
, where 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1292,1436,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[1292,1436,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occurs. Based on this, we may suppose, (without complete certainty) that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[1042,1185,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[1042,1185,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[1242,1394,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[1242,1394,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are reproductively isolated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,608]" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">
The most evident external differences between the two species are: scutellum surrounded by dense and isolated pubescence (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[297,448,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[297,448,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) / scutellum not surrounded by dense pubescence, or the pubescence is not isolated (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); dense pubescence on basal half of the elytra forming two isolated maculae, the first one inclined toward humerus (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tippmann" authorityYear="1960" box="[265,418,512,536]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zapotensis">
<emphasis box="[265,418,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. zapotensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) / dense pubescence on basal half of the elytra forming a longitudinal band with anterior area curved inward (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sturm" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[385,528,549,572]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Ornithia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicana">
<emphasis box="[385,528,549,572]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="75">O. mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The study of the male genitalia of both species showed no difference between them.
</paragraph>
